>>15106301
I haven't read anything from your green yet, but judging from this post you need a lot more practice.
Your pacing is way too fast, making the lewd scene unfulfilling and seemingly pointless. Notice how you're beginning many lines with "I". Try to have variety in your structure; we're here to read a well-thought-out story; not a child's summary of their day.
In short, focus on details. Elaborate on scenes that you find important. Hobo's otter story had several thousand words of prose going over Anon and Tin's lovemaking session, going from Tin's lingerie to finding out which letter was best to mimic when performing cunnilingus on her dripping sex.
>>I find her G-spot and start focusing my attention on it
That's providing info to the reader, but it's not enough. You providing a start and an end, but what people care about the most is the journey between it. We know that most capeshit movies have the main characters winning in the end, but what we pay attention to the most is their struggles and interactions with each other, making us empathize with them. have If you're having trouble writing longer scenes, I suggest reading more lewds and learn writing techniques from them to build on your own voice.
This isn't meant to discourage you from continuing to write in any way, but I hope you spend more time on refining your story. Read over it several times over several drafts. Your update schedule is fast, but what's important is quality over quantity. Actively seek out parts that are lacking and amend them because it's much more satisfying to have everything click together after rereading the same scene countless times over to make sure that you wrote it to the best of your abilities. Write what you care about, and make sure others will care about it, too.

>>15107831
You know what's fucking funny about this question? Back when I was just a lil' Hobo in elementary school, I HATED writing. The idea of writing more than one paragraph felt like wasted effort.

I can only offer two possible explanations as to why I became able to vomit out words.
1. I started roleplaying. Text roleplay, not table top. I just enjoyed participating in what was effectively multiplayer story telling. At this point I've been doing it for some ten years now.
2. College, and so many nights typing up papers the night before an assignment was due. Crunch time is a life style.

>>15107899
>I've never been able to predict that on-a-roll thing though, nor have I managed to reliably induce it.
The only piece of advice I can give about this is to not rely on "being in the mood" or waiting for inspiration to write. This advice doesn't mesh well with some peoples' methods here (Ret is running a quest, and durr_anon's stuff reads like it's 90% stream of consciousness), but if you're writing anything substantial you're going to have to hunker down and get to work.

Have a dedicated time where you sit down and write, and for how long and/or how much. Don't go "Hm, it's six o'clock. I think I'll stop playing vidya after this mission and write a bit." That doesn't work, because you'll just keep playing vidya, or stare at a blinking line waiting for 'the good stuff.'
No more bullshit. Six o'clock hits and you stop what you're doing, and you write for an hour. Minimum 1000 words, but if you get there before your hour is up then you best keep pushing. Writing is the martial arts of language; you have to dedicate yourself to it if you don't want to be some weak nameless mook writer #3 who gets BTFO in the bar scene by a well thought out one liner.
It's like some One Punch Man shit. You know: 10 paragraphs, 1000 words, 2 pages, every day.
Consistency breeds work ethic, and work ethic is what drags you feet first through writing blocks when you have to deliver.

>Don't wait for inspiration
Believe me, I don't. I treat writing as a sort of default activity that I engage in whenever not doing something else, and usually for a minimum of an hour or two each night. Most sessions just aren't that productive. I'm a "basher", and usually settle into cyclic revision patterns instead. I could probably be faster if I drafted, but I'm usually happier with the results of agonizing paragraph by paragraph. The downside is, if I don't start with something I'm in love with, I spend a lot more time re-writing. The core of Chapter six of Silver Lining was probably re-written and rebuilt in various forms five or so times before I hit on how I wanted it.

Some nights it just isn't a problem, though. Almost all of chapter five came out in a single sitting.
